In C#, a vector of shorts can be represented using an array of short data type. Here's an example of how you can create and initialize a vector of shorts:

```csharp
short[] vector = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
```

This creates an array of shorts with 5 elements and initializes it with the values 1, 2, 3, 4, and 5. You can access individual elements of the vector using their index. For example, to get the value at index 0:

```csharp
short firstElement = vector[0];
```

You can also modify individual elements by assigning new values to them:

```csharp
vector[2] = 10;
```

Now, the value at index 2 will be 10.

Note that arrays in C# are zero-indexed, so the first element is at index 0.

If you need a dynamic vector that can grow or shrink in size, you can use the `List<short>` class from the `System.Collections.Generic` namespace. Here's an example of how to use a `List<short>`:

```csharp
List<short> vector = new List<short>();
vector.Add(1);
vector.Add(2);
vector.Add(3);
```

This creates a dynamic vector and adds the values 1, 2, and 3 to it. You can access and modify individual elements in the same way as with arrays.

In the code snippet `InputSystem.AddDevice(new InputDeviceDescription { /* rest of code */ });`, the `new` keyword is used to create a new instance of the `InputDeviceDescription` class. 

The `new` keyword is used for object instantiation in C#. It allocates memory for an object and initializes its fields by invoking the constructor. In this case, a new instance of `InputDeviceDescription` is created and passed as an argument to the `AddDevice` method of the `InputSystem` class.

Here's a simpler example to demonstrate the usage of the `new` keyword:

```csharp
// Define a class
class Person
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }
}

// Instantiate a new instance of the class using `new`
Person person1 = new Person();
person1.Name = "John";
person1.Age = 25;
```

In this example, we create a custom `Person` class with two properties: `Name` and `Age`. Then, we use the `new` keyword to create a new instance of the `Person` class and assign values to its properties.

The `new` keyword is essential for creating and initializing objects in C#. It allows you to allocate memory for an object and set its initial state before using it in your code.
